56
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:20,000
There were lots of people who knew that E over C squared was equal to m.

57
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:25,000
But it took the genius of Einstein to realize that m is equal to C squared.

58
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:26,000
True.

59
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:27,000
All right.

60
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:28,000
So we put another C in here.

61
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:30,000
It's C downstairs.

62
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:31,000
But I don't really care.

63
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:33,000
Now this is m.

64
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:38,000
I don't really care where the C's are because we're going to set them equal to 1.

65
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:48,000
So the only point of this was to say the units of mass, when we set C equal to 1,

66
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:50,000
are the same as the units of Planck's constant.

67
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:52,000
So we set Planck's constant over length.

68
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:56,000
But if we also set Planck's constant equal to 1,

69
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:58,000
then the units of mass are 1 over length.

70
00:04:58,000 --> 00:04:59,000
So keep that in mind.

71
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:05,000
Mass is 1 over length in units, unit-wise.

72
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:08,000
Now, what about the units of G?

73
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,000
We have not set G equal to 1.

74
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:12,000
G has units.

75
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:16,000
It's not too hard to figure out what the units of G are.

76
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:18,000
We just take, again, some equation that has G in it.

77
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:19,000
And we just take, again, some equation that has G in it.

78
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:22,000
And we look at its...

79
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:28,000
What's the simplest equation that contains G?

80
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:32,000
Acceleration equals mass times G over R squared.

81
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:33,000
Good.

82
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:41,000
Acceleration equals G m over R squared.

83
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:45,000
Now, the left-hand side, what's the units of the left-hand side?

84
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:48,000
L over T squared.

85
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:49,000
L over T squared.

86
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:50,000
L over T squared.

87
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:55,000
We need a...

88
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:59,000
Is length over time squared.

89
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:03,000
But length and time have the same units when C is equal to 1.

90
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:11,000
So this is just length over length squared, which is 1 over length, right?

91
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:13,000
R squared, of course, is length squared.

92
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:17,000
So let's call this length squared.

93
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:19,000
And now we can multiply both sides of the equation by length.

94
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:21,000
And now we can multiply both sides of the equation by length squared.

95
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:24,000
And this becomes length upstairs.

96
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:26,000
Oh, we knew that before, didn't we?

97
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:27,000
That's the radius...

98
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:33,000
This is the Schwarzschild radius, or proportional to the Schwarzschild radius of a black hole.

99
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:37,000
But now a mass is 1 over a length.

100
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:39,000
Inverse length.

101
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:44,000
And so we can write that the mass is 1 over a length.

102
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:46,000
Transfer it to the other side.

103
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,000
And we discover that in this case, we have a mass.

104
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:56,000
We discover that in these units, G has units of an area.

105
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:58,000
What area?

106
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:02,000
There's only one area around that it could be.

107
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:04,000
It's the Planck area.

108
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:10,000
All right, so G is in fact not only an area.

109
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:16,000
It's also the Planck area squared.

110
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:18,000
That's an important equation.

111
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:29,000
In fact, that helps us understand why it is that the entropy of a black hole is the area divided by 4 times G.

112
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:31,000
Forget the 4.

113
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:33,000
It's the area divided by G.

114
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:37,000
It's the area in Planck units, is what it is.

115
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:40,000
Okay, so that's one equation.

116
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:42,000
Now, there's another fact.

117
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:44,000
And that's that G, of course, also has...

118
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:45,000
It's not a mass.

119
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:47,000
It's not just a length squared.

120
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:50,000
It does have to do with the strength of gravity.

121
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:59,000
Okay, so let's think about it in the context of string theory as having to do with the force of gravity.

122
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:01,000
What does the force of gravity come from?

123
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:03,000
The force of gravity...

124
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:06,000
And no explanation of this tonight.

125
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:07,000
This is not for tonight.

126
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:09,000
We've talked about it before.

127
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:11,000
This is just a cartoon.

128
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:13,000
The force of gravity between two objects.

129
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:14,000
This could be the Earth.

130
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:16,000
This could be the Moon over here.

131
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:19,000
It's due to the exchange of gravitons.

132
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:21,000
How does that happen in string theory?

133
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:24,000
Well, everything is made up out of strings.

134
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:26,000
A little string breaks off.

135
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:27,000
How does it break off?

136
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:31,000
It breaks off...

137
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:40,000
When the string crosses itself, there is a probability that when a string...

138
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:42,000
Can everybody see this string?

139
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:44,000
Oh, boy.

140
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:45,000
No, let's see.

141
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:48,000
We want to turn this hand around, keep that hand...

142
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:49,000
Okay.

143
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:54,000
When the string crosses itself, that it can rearrange.

144
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:55,000
All right?

145
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:58,000
That when the string crosses itself, that it can rearrange.

146
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:03,000
That probability, or the square root of that probability, strictly speaking,

147
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:10,000
the square root of it, is called the amplitude for string rearrangement.

148
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:11,000
Okay?

149
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:14,000
Rearrangement, or string breaking, or whatever.

150
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:16,000
It's not really breaking.

151
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:17,000
It's rearrangement.

152
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:18,000
And it's called little g.

153
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:20,000
We've talked about it before.

154
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:21,000
Little g.

155
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:26,000
The main thing about it is it's a square root of a probability,

156
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:30,000
and a probability has no units.

157
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:32,000
So it's dimensionless.

158
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:37,000
There's little g, which is the probability that when a string crosses itself,

159
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:39,000
it breaks off a little piece.

160
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:40,000
That little piece...

161
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:45,000
That little piece jumps across to another thing,

162
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:48,000
rearranges again,

163
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:51,000
so that the string jumps from one side to the other.

164
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:54,000
That, in string theory, is the Feynman diagram,

165
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:56,000
or the analog of the Feynman diagram,

166
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:59,000
which has to do with the forces between the two sides.

167
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:04,000
And the important thing is that it's proportional to two powers of this g.

168
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:07,000
One to emit the little string,

169
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:09,000
and one to absorb the little string.

170
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:16,000
That tells us that the force of gravity is proportional to little g squared.

171
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:21,000
So what it must tell us then,

172
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:28,000
is that little g squared

173
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:32,000
must be proportional to Newton's constant.

174
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:35,000
Newton's constant is the strength of gravity.

175
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:38,000
Little g is the probability for break of strength.

176
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:41,000
Newton's constant is the probability for break of strength breaking.

177
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:43,000
But this can't be right.

178
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:45,000
The left-hand side is dimensionless,

179
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:47,000
has no dimensions, it's just a probability.

180
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:50,000
The right-hand side has units of area.

181
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:53,000
So there has to be something else in here

182
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:55,000
to make up the units,

183
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:59,000
to give you an area on the left side.

184
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:01,000
What is that?

185
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:05,000
That has to do with the fundamental length scale of string theory.

186
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:07,000
It's not the Planck length.

187
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:11,000
It's the fundamental length scale of string theory.

188
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:14,000
It is basically,

189
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:16,000
if you look at a long wiggly string,

190
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:19,000
you'll discover, inevitably,

191
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:21,000
it consists of little wiggles,

192
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:24,000
it random walks, but it has little wiggles,

193
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:27,000
and it's basically the size of the little wiggles.

194
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:30,000
Basic size of the little wiggles,

195
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:34,000
and it's called L-string.

196
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:36,000
We've talked about it before,

197
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:39,000
I'm just reminding you.

198
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:42,000
It's the only other variable around in the problem.

199
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:47,000
This is L-Planck squared.

200
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:49,000
This side is string theory,

201
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:52,000
this side is gravity.

202
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:57,000
Gravity tells us that this side is L-Planck squared.

203
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:00,000
The only sensible equation that I can write

204
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:04,000
that only contains things that have to do with string theory on this side

205
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:07,000
is to say that this is G squared,

206
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:09,000
times L-string squared.

207
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:11,000
And that's the correct equation.

208
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:15,000
That is the correct equation that

209
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:19,000
the Planck length squared, which is the same as big G,

210
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:22,000
is little g squared times L-string squared.

211
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:24,000
Now just think about what that means.

212
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:27,000
That means that

213
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:32,000
if little g were tiny,

214
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:34,000
a tiny number,

215
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:36,000
gravity would be very weak,

216
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:38,000
and what it would tell us

217
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:43,000
is that the Planck length was much, much smaller than the string length.

218
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:47,000
So in fact, this G, this little g which appears here,

219
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:49,000
can also be thought of

220
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:54,000
as having to do with the relative size of the Planck length scale,

221
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:57,000
the length scale that has to do with gravity,

222
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:59,000
and the string length scale.

223
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:03,000
In fact, we can even take the square root of this equation.

224
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:04,000
Let's do so.

225
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:10,000
It says

226
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:14,000
that L-Planck is G times L-string.

227
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:17,000
Okay, so that's another equation I want to write down here.

228
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:23,000
L-Planck is equal to G times L-string.

229
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:28,000
What other equations do we need?

230
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:30,000
All right, next equation.

231
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:32,000
Just make a list of them

232
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:34,000
before we try to use them

233
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:36,000
and before we try to derive anything.

234
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:41,000
Next equation, the entropy of a string.

235
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:44,000
The entropy of a string S.

236
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:46,000
Now remember,

237
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:50,000
entropy basically counts the number of decisions,

238
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:55,000
yes, no, or up, down, or left, right decisions

239
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:57,000
that you have to make to describe a system.

240
00:13:57,000 --> 00:13:59,000
Let's just leave it at that.

241
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:04,000
It's the number of primitive binary,

242
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:05,000
doesn't matter what's binary,

243
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:07,000
it could be trinary,

244
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:08,000
or quadrinary,

245
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:10,000
or some small number.

246
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:12,000
Number of decisions that you have to make

247
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:15,000
to specify a configuration.

248
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:17,000
I gave you a little example

249
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:20,000
of a model for string theory.

250
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:23,000
And it's a reasonably good model for string theory.

251
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:26,000
It's one that statistical mechanics people use all the time,

252
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:29,000
not for string theory, but for other purposes,

253
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:31,000
where they replace a string

254
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:34,000
by a series of links of a line.

255
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:37,000
Links of a lattice, and so forth.

256
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:39,000
Link can go back on itself,

257
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:41,000
